    {
      "id": "j501-h2-mcp-server",
      "type": "MARKDOWN",
      "mode": "jshell",
      "source": "## 1. MCP Server Overview\n\nVenus implements **JSON-RPC 2.0** over HTTP+SSE (the standard MCP transport).\n\n### Available Tools (8)\n\n| Tool | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `venus_execute_code` | Run Java code in a JShell session |\n| `venus_list_notebooks` | List all notebooks with metadata |\n| `venus_read_notebook` | Read all cells from a notebook |\n| `venus_run_pipeline` | Execute a pipeline with dependency resolution |\n| `venus_search_cells` | Search cells by anchor name or content |\n| `venus_load_module` | Load a named cell module into a session |\n| `venus_create_notebook` | Create a new notebook (optionally with cells) |\n| `venus_append_cell` | Add a cell to a notebook and optionally execute it |\n\n### MCP Transport\n\n```\nClient → POST /api/mcp/messages  (JSON-RPC 2.0 request)\nServer → HTTP response            (JSON-RPC 2.0 result)\nServer → GET /api/mcp/sse        (SSE stream for server-push events)\n```",
      "output": "",
      "returnValue": null,
      "executed": false,
      "executionCount": null,
      "error": "",
      "anchor": null,
      "dependsOn": [],
      "pipelineSteps": []
    },
    {
      "id": "j501-h2-claude-desktop",
      "type": "MARKDOWN",
      "mode": "jshell",
      "source": "## 2. Connect Claude Desktop\n\nAdd to `%APPDATA%\\Claude\\claude_desktop_config.json` (Windows) or `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json` (macOS):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"venus-notebooks\": {\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:8585/api/mcp/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nRestart Claude Desktop. In any conversation you can now say:\n\n> *\"List my Venus notebooks\"*  \n> *\"Run the ETL pipeline in java-401\"*  \n> *\"Execute `IntStream.range(1,11).sum()` in Java\"*  \n> *\"Create a notebook called 'Data Analysis' with a imports cell\"*\n\nClaude will call the appropriate `venus_*` tool automatically.",
      "output": "",
      "returnValue": null,
      "executed": false,
      "executionCount": null,
      "error": "",
      "anchor": null,
      "dependsOn": [],
      "pipelineSteps": []
    },
    {
      "id": "j501-h2-claude-code",
      "type": "MARKDOWN",
      "mode": "jshell",
      "source": "## 3. Connect Claude Code (CLI)\n\nClaude Code supports MCP servers via `.claude/settings.json` in your project directory, or via the global `~/.claude/settings.json`.\n\n### Option A — Project-level (`.claude/settings.json`)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"venus\": {\n      \"command\": \"node\",\n      \"args\": [\"-e\", \"...\"],\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:8585/api/mcp/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Option B — Direct HTTP in Claude Code prompts\n\nSince Claude Code can also call tools via the `/api/mcp/messages` endpoint directly, you can instruct it:\n\n> *\"Use the Venus MCP server at http://localhost:8585 to list all notebooks and execute the imports cell from java-401\"*\n\nClaude Code will use `WebFetch` to call the REST API directly.\n\n### Useful Claude Code prompts with Venus\n\n```bash\n# In your project dir, with Venus MCP configured:\nclaude \"List all Venus notebooks and show me the cells in java-401\"\nclaude \"Run the ETL pipeline in java-401 and show me the output\"\nclaude \"Create a new Venus notebook called 'My Analysis' and add a cell that computes the fibonacci sequence\"\n```",
      "output": "",
      "returnValue": null,
      "executed": false,
      "executionCount": null,
      "error": "",
      "anchor": null,
      "dependsOn": [],
      "pipelineSteps": []
